Bangladesh: US Experts Identify Virus of "Mysterious Disease" in Tangail
---------------------------------------------------
Medical experts at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in
Atlanta, USA, have identified the "mysterious disease" that has already
taken several lives in Tangail, an official handout said here yesterday
(Mon 24 Jan 2005). CDC experts found Nipah virus in the blood of patients.
The disease, which has claimed some lives in the district, created a panic
among the [local population].
Nipah virus is [named after] a place in Malaysia. According to medical
experts, Nipah virus is carried by bats. Anybody eating fruit contaminated
by bat excreta or in contact with bat excreta could contract Nipah virus
infection.
The handout said that after receiving notification of the death of one
person in Tangail, a medical team of experts from Institute of
Epidemiological Disease Control and Research (IEDCR) under the Health
Directorate rushed to the area to investigate on 11 Jan 2005. Later, on 16
Jan 2005, the Director General of Health Services visited the affected
area. The medical teams formed by the Tangail Civil Surgeon are also
working round-the-clock in the affected area.
The IEDCR experts have sent samples of blood, urine, [sputum] and CSF
(cerebrospinal fluid) to the CDC in Atlanta for further investigation. The
CDC experts disclosed their findings on 20 Jan 2005, saying that Nipah
virus was found in the blood samples. The handout said [urgent] steps have
been taken to [contain] the disease. The Tangail medical team and IEDCR
experts will continue their work.
--
Dr.med.vet FVH Christian Griot
