Source: Chinaview website/ Xinhuanet News Agency, Tue 25 Jan 2995 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-01/25/content_2505294.htm>

Bangladesh: Virus Killing 5 Confirmed to be Nipah Virus
--------------------------------------------------
5 deaths in central Bangladesh have been confirmed to be caused by Nipah
virus, as more than 20 other patients have been reported to be suffering
from the viral infection since 5 Jan 2005. A release by the Directorate
General of Health Services (DGHS) on Tue 25 Jan 2005 confirmed the outbreak
of Nipah virus in the northern district of Tangail, adjacent to Dhaka.
According to the release, the health department one week ago sent the
samples of blood, human tissue, and urine from the infected patients to the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in Atlanta, GA, USA. The
CDC on 20 Jan 2005 sent the results that show some samples are Nipah
virus-positive.
So far there have been 12 deaths from the infection in January with
flu-like symptoms including high fever and muscle pains, while many
villagers in the district have begun to flee their homes in panic. The DGHS
in the wake of the CDC report has taken immediate measures to further
investigate the mode of transmission and epidemiology of the virus.
Nipah virus draws its name from a Malaysian village where it was first
detected in 1999. The virus causes disease in animals and then in humans
through contact with infected animals. In a large outbreak of encephalitis
in Malaysia in 1999, the investigation identified Nipah virus as the causal
agent, and 105 out of 265 infected people died. The virus was also detected
in Bangladesh in January-February 2004, killing 18 people, mostly children.
According to World Health Organization data, no drug therapies have yet
been proven effective in treating Nipah virus infection. Treatment relies
on intensive supportive care. There is some evidence that early treatment
with the antiviral drug [ribavirin?] can reduce both the duration of fever
and the severity of disease. The efficacy of this treatment in curing the
disease or improving survival, however, is still uncertain.
