Source: The New Nation, Tue 25 Jan 2005 [edited]
<http://nation.ittefaq.com/artman/publish/article_15671.shtml>

Bangladesh: Rapid Response Teams to Prevent Spread of Nipha Virus
--------------------------------------------------
The government has appointed 'rapid response teams' in every district to
detect and prevent spread of Nipah virus infection About 11 people died due
to Nipah virus infection in the Tangail district during the past few days.
Earlier in 2004 about 24 people died [in an outbreak of Nipah virus
infection] in the Faridpur district. Experts say if the virus spreads man
to man, the attack may take epidemic proportions.
Director of the Institute of Epidemiology Disease Control and Research
(IEDCR) Mahmudur Rahman said, "We are working to prepare a set of
guidelines for people to prevent infection by the virus. We are going to
investigate the source of the virus. If we can detect the source it will be
very easy to prevent the disease," he said.
Quoting researchers from Atlanta [CDC], he also said the virus is spread by
bats. The virus can also spread from human to human, he added, [citing a]
BBC report.
