[4]
Date: Tue 25 Jan 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Daily Star, Tue 25 Jan 2005 [edited]
<http://www.thedailystar.net/2005/01/25/d5012501098.htm>

Bangladesh: Tangail Deaths Caused by Nipah Virus
------------------------------------------------
Medical experts yesterday confirmed an outbreak of Nipah virus infection in
3 villages in Tangail, where 5 people died and 25 more were reported
suffering from viral infection since 5 Jan 2005.
The Directorate General of Health Services (DGHS) in a press release
yesterday confirmed the Nipah outbreak. It said samples of blood and tissue
from sick patients had been sent to the Centres for Disease Control and
Prevention (CDC) in Atlanta, GA, USA. The CDC on 20 Jan 2005 conveyed the
test report that shows one patient is Nipah virus-positive.
[Nipah virus] transmission from animal to human requires close contact with
contaminated tissue or body fluids from infected animals. The DGHS, in the
wake of the CDC report, has taken immediate measures to further investigate
the mode of transmission and epidemiology of the virus. It is also
collecting more samples to analyse suspected illness among other
neighbouring inhabitants in the affected villages in Habla union in Basail.
"We're very alarmed by the result and now have no doubts that the 'unknown'
viral attack in Tangail is a Nipah virus outbreak," said Prof Mahmudur
Rahman, director of Institute of Epidemiology, Disease Control and Research
(IEDCR).
"The high mortality rate is more alarming in Bangladesh if we consider the
Nipah virus outbreaks in Goalanda in Faridpur and Meherpur a few of years
back," he added. The rate in Malaysia, where the virus was discovered or
suspected to have originated, was 39 percent, whereas in Faridpur it was 73
percent.
According to the World Health Organisation (WHO), Nipah virus was
discovered in 1999. It causes disease in animals and then in humans through
contact with infected animals. Certain species of fruit bats are currently
believed to have been the hosts of the virus. Antibodies to the virus have
been detected in pigs and other domestic and wild animals, according to the
WHO. However, the role of species other than pigs in transmitting Nipah
virus has not yet been determined. It is unlikely that the virus is easily
transmitted to man, although previous outbreak reports suggest Nipah virus
is transmitted from animals to humans more readily.
Despite frequent contact between fruit bats and humans, there is no
serological evidence of human infection from bat carriers. Pigs were the
apparent source of infection among most human cases in the Malaysian
outbreak, but other sources such as infected dogs and cats cannot be ruled
out, said a WHO release, which also said the incubation period of the virus
is between 4 and 18 days. In many cases the infection is mild or not
apparent (sub-clinical). In symptomatic cases, the onset is usually with
'influenza-like' symptoms, with high fever and muscle pains. The disease
may progress to inflammation of the brain (encephalitis) with drowsiness,
disorientation, convulsions, and coma. 50 percent of clinically apparent
cases die.
Between September 1998 and April 1999, there was a large outbreak of
encephalitis in Malaysia. During investigation, Nipah virus, a previously
unrecognised virus, was identified as the causal agent. As many as 265
people were infected and 105 of them died.
